{{Infobox park |name = Alexandra Fountain |photo = File:Alexandra Fountain, Charing Cross, Bendigo, Victoria, Australia.jpg |alt = |photo_caption = View of Alexandra Fountain in Charing Cross, Bendigo, Victoria, Australia |type = Fountain |location = [[Bendigo]], [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]], Australia |coords = {{coord|-36.75961|144.27828|format=dms|type:landmark_region:AU-VIC|display=inline,title}} |opened = 5 July 1881 |owner = [[City of Greater Bendigo]] }}
'''Alexandra Fountain''' is regarded as one of [[Bendigo]], [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]], Australia's most prominent landmarks and monuments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC20CQR_alexandra-fountain?guid=03274844-3a83-47c5-b2e0-0858278d1318 |title=GC20CQR Alexandra Fountain (Earthcache) in Victoria, Australia|publisher=Geocaching.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-13}}</ref>
The fountain is located in Bendigo's "Charing Cross", the intersection of View Street and Pall Mall. Charing Cross effectively stands at the centre of the city and is one of Bendigo's busiest and most prominent intersections. The fountain stands opposite to the main entrance of Rosalind Park.
Alexandra Fountain was funded from the proceeds of the Bendigo Juvenile Industrial Exhibition (1879), a £500 gift from George Lansell and a further £700 from the Sandhurst City Council (now the [[City of Greater Bendigo]]). The fountain was designed by [[W. C. Vahland]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bendigo.ws/Our-History/Architecture-and-Buildings/Alexandra-Fountain.html |title=Alexandra Fountain - Bendigo, Victoria, Australia |publisher=Bendigo.ws |date=2007-09-22 |accessdate=2015-03-13}}</ref> a local architect responsible for some of the cities most prominent buildings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bendigo.ws/Our-History/People/William-Charles-Vahland.html |title=William Charles Vahland - Bendigo Pioneer |publisher=Bendigo.ws |date= |accessdate=2015-03-13}}</ref> The fountain was named in honour of [[Alexandra of Denmark|Alexandra]], Princess of Wales and the grand opening (5 July 1881) was attended by her sons [[Prince Albert Victor, Duke of Clarence and Avondale|Prince Albert]] and [[George V|Prince George]].<ref name="autogeneratedvic">{{cite web|url=http://vhd.heritage.vic.gov.au/search/nattrust_result_detail/68184 |title=Alexandra Fountain |publisher=Vhd.heritage.vic.gov.au |date=2010-07-30 |accessdate=2015-03-13}}</ref>
Other than the Exhibition Fountain, built in 1880 and located in the [[Melbourne]]'s [[Carlton Gardens]], the Alexandra Fountain is the largest and most ornate municipal fountain in Victoria.<ref name="autogeneratedvic"/> The fountain stands {{convert|28|ft|m}} high and sits in a {{convert|50|ft|m}} diameter circular pool which itself is {{convert|2|ft|m}} deep. It is made from {{convert|20|tonne}} of Harcourt granite, cast iron and painted stone. Decoratively the fountain includes lion head spouts, four allegorical female figures, spouted bronzed mer-horses and dolphins, medallions of seashells, dolphins and tridents also decorate the fountain. The pool is bordered by a decorative cast iron fence and lit with four cast iron lamps.<ref name="autogeneratedvic"/>
Historically the fountain is a monument to the success of the Goldfields and the Bendigo region. Aesthetically the fountain is fairly typical of late Victorian monumental design but is unusual in that few fountains were built according to this theme.<ref name="autogeneratedvic"/>
As of 2017 a AU$350,000 refurbishment project is underway. The restoration project will include repairs and repainting of the balustrade and masonry, including repainting and re-rendering the plaster work as well as plumbing and electrical work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bendigo.vic.gov.au/About/News-and-media/Media-Releases/city-set-commence-restoration-historic-alexandra-fountain|title=City set to commence restoration of historic Alexandra Fountain {{!}} City of Greater Bendigo|website=www.bendigo.vic.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2017-11-13}}</ref>
